      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Sharp knee pain that came on after a long run and hurts on stairs is something a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor needs to assess in person. That's not me being cautious for the sake of it. Knee pain has several possible sources, and the right response depends on what's actually causing it. Guessing wrong can make things worse.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question: that's outside my lane. It's a medical decision, and you'd want a doctor's input before using any medication to manage pain around training.\n\nOn continuing to run: I'd hold off until you've had it looked at. Running through sharp pain without knowing the cause is a real risk. Two weeks is long enough that this warrants a proper assessment, not a workaround.\n\nWhat I can do is work with you once you have some clarity from a professional. A physio visit doesn't necessarily mean weeks off. It means you'll know what you're actually dealing with, and we can build a plan around that. Your half marathon is July 11. That gives us reasonable time to work with, depending on what comes back.\n\nA few things worth bringing to your appointment: when exactly the pain started, whether it's sharp or aching, whether it's localized to one spot on the knee, and how it behaves during versus after running. That kind of detail helps them work faster.\n\nCome back once you've seen someone and we'll figure out the path forward from there."
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01S1ypiu45R1dfpqpfcjLVjp"
    }
  ],
